  "chunk_index": 37,
  "summary": "Inspector Huishe informs Dr. Arthur Calgary that Mr. Darlant, a disabled man suffering from polio, is conducting his own amateur detective work regarding the murder at Sunset Corner. Huishe observes that while Darlant is intuitive and intelligent, he is likely to keep his findings private. Calgary expresses concern that the truth must be revealed to those involved, though Huishe suggests they may already be aware of it.\n\nCalgary later visits Molly Craig, who discusses rumors surrounding a murder case involving a man named Joe, who was previously pardoned after claiming innocence. Molly speculates that Joe's brother, Mickey, might be the true culprit due to his unpredictable nature and a potential plan to escape to Persia. She also mentions rumors of a husband and secretary being involved, suggesting the possibility of a murder committed via poison.\n\nSeeking information for a book on pathological personalities, Calgary meets with a middle-aged woman. He uses his experience from the Hayes-Bentley Expedition to Antarctica to build rapport with her. The woman describes Jacquie as a charming individual potentially motivated by money. She reveals that she had plans to travel to France or Italy with Jacquie if his schemes had succeeded.\n\nIn a separate scene, Philip Durrant wakes up feeling refreshed and anticipates a visit from Tina. His wife, Mary (Polly), informs him that Hester is coming home. This news causes brief tension between the couple when Philip dismisses Mary's implication that he harbors inappropriate feelings for Tina.",
